article.headline: Rutgers 77, Temple 67
article.story: PISCATAWAY, N.J. (AP) -- Freshman Quincy Douby scored a career-high 21 points and Rutgers pulled away in the second half for a 77-67 victory over Temple Wednesday night. Rutgers (3-1) still trails the series, 31-16, but has won three of its last four against Temple (0-3) and snapped a three-game home losing streak to the Owls. Douby shot 7-for-11 and 4-for-6 from 3-point range, and Rutgers was 12-for-23 on 3-pointers. Herve Lamizana added 15 points and seven rebounds for Rutgers while Ricky Shields had 14 points and seven rebounds. Freshman Marquis Webb had nine points and eight assists. Temple had its best shooting night of the year but still hit only 41.8 percent and was 6-for-23 from behind the arc. Mardy Collins had a career-high 22 for Temple and David Hawkins had 18. Holding a nine-point halftime lead, Rutgers gradually built its advantage to 77-57 with 3:28 left. Douby hit a 3-pointer to give Rutgers a 14-11 lead with 12:45 left in the first half and Rutgers never trailed again. With the score 54-43, Douby hit two straight 3-pointers and Webb added another 3-pointer as Rutgers opened a 63-48 advantage. In the first half, Rutgers rallied from a 9-2 deficit for a 16-11 lead. Temple cut it to 21-20 before the Scarlet Knights used a 14-4 run to open its biggest lead of the half, 35-24. Rutgers led 37-28 at halftime after holding the Owls to 35.7 percent shooting. Douby had 11 points on 4-for-7 shooting. Temple stayed in it thanks to 7-for-7 shooting from the foul line. Earlier in the day, Temple coach John Chaney suspended reserve sophomore forward Micheal Blackshear for a violation of team rules. The suspension will last at least until the end of the first semester. Blackshear averaged 3.0 points and 3.0 rebounds in the Owls' first two games.
